Task: The company client wants to know which potential markets are the most interesting for the newline of products of sports market and it is interested in knowing the Covid-19 impact on mobility.

Target/Purpose: develop a new service or adapt exsisting one depends on the situation

introduction: The COVID-19 pandemic influences the behavior of the people. One behavior that changes is mobility. Changes in behavior affect economic conditions in an area. The knowledge gained can be a reference in making accurate and right decisions. These decisions are taken to mitigate the risks and impacts felt by the community. https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-6596/1833/1/012002/pdf. we want to explore data gained from maps of apple to to make a decision meets our goal for the best potenial market

Dataset: The data used is COVID-19 Community Mobility Report. The data is in the form of a table that contains mobility data for each country. Some countries are also equipped with data for each region and subregion. The data displayed includes certain dates that are quite complete.
we want to explore data gained from maps of apple to to make a decision meets oor goal for the best potenial market

Dealing with missing values

Depending on our analysis, we will deal with missing values, which are represented here by NA (not available). For example, we can take the mean of the variable and fill in the missing values with the result. However, we will be working in specific areas. So, we don’t have to do that, instead, we will remove these values.

Check for the missing values in the reqoust

sum(is.na(mobility$req_num)) #is.na to check for missing values and with sum func we weill know the count
## [1] 13802

Visualizing missing values in our dataframe

vis_miss(mobility, warn_large_data = F) #from "visdat" Package

Remove the rows with missing data from the “request counts” coloumn

new_mob <- mobility %>% filter(!is.na(req_num))  #from dplyr library

#test again for NA values
sum(is.na(new_mob$req_num))
## [1] 0

univariate qualitative analysis

analysis of a single categorical variable-

Frequency bar chart-
#plot barplot fro the transportaion type
ggplot(target_market, aes(x=transportation_type)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=region))+ #use fill arg in aestestics enables us to choose the filled color depend on the region
  ggtitle("Graph Shows equal behaviour of mobility between the different means of transport")+
  theme_minimal() # prefer to choose the minimal theme for better Visualisation not to disratct our Audience wth useless stuff

so we wanna adjust our Product to fit the different types of transport. this may be easy to think that we are dealing with same kind , but may be challenging as well. because we have to take into account different transport types

#plot barplot fro the transportaion type
ggplot(target_market, aes(x=transportation_type)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=region), position = "dodge")+ #use fill arg in aestestics enables us to choose the filled color depend on the region
  ggtitle("Graph Shows equal behaviour of mobility between the different means of transport")+
  theme_minimal() # prefer to choose the minimal theme for better Visualisation not to disratct our Audience with useless stuff

#instead of putting the filtered data into a variable I choosed to use the pipe operator which cast it to the ggplot function
filter(target_market,transportation_type=="walking") %>% ggplot( aes(x = date, y = req_num )) +
  geom_line(aes(color =  region )) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 100, color = "gray40") +
  labs(x = "Date",
    y = "Total requests",
    title = "Map Requests decrease dramatically with time at the begining of the pandemic ",
    subtitle = "a slight increase again in brazil compared to Germany and US")+
    theme_minimal()
